I actually think that Apple does an excellent job of striking that balance =
today. When it comes to the iPhone itself, Apple is the only entity that ca=
n make it truly secure; no individual can build their own secure enclave th=
at sits at the root of iPhone security. Therefore, they are right to do so:=
 everyone has access to encryption.

From there it is possible to build a fully secure environment: use only enc=
rypted communications, use encrypted backups to a computer secured by its o=
wn hardware-based authentication scheme, etc. Taking the slightly easier ro=
ute, though =E2=80=94 iCloud backups, Facebook messaging, etc. =E2=80=94 me=
ans some degree of vulnerability that, let=E2=80=99s not forget, is sometim=
es justifiably leveraged. Law enforcement can get a warrant for those backu=
ps or chat logs, just as they can install a wire tap.

Again, this isn=E2=80=99t going to stop determined bad actors, but as I not=
ed, nothing is. The question is what of the rest, those that get swept up b=
y the worst sort of communities, and who commit legitimate crimes: what sho=
uld their defaults be?

I should also note that I am skeptical that this philosophy is what actuall=
y undergirds Apple=E2=80=99s thinking. I suspect their reasoning is much mo=
re utilitarian: holding the key to iCloud backups keeps the FBI off of thei=
r back, and it lets them operate iCloud in China (remember, the keys are st=
ored locally). It is the most pragmatic way to have their public privacy ca=
ke and eat it too.

I think that whole Update is worth a re-visit, particularly the parts where=
 I split up the warring factions on this issue into "Math Fatalists", "Priv=
acy Fundamentalists", and "Law and Order". The conclusion that I reached in=
 the above excerpt, however, is that encryption should not be illegal =E2=
=80=94 and Apple should not be compelled to put backdoors into iPhones =E2=
=80=94 but it's ok if the most convenient cloud complements to a user's dev=
ices are not end-to-end encrypted; that's a compromise position that gives =
each faction a bit of what they want, if not everything.

What I think the U.K. would argue is that it is Apple that broke this uneas=
y compromise by offering Advanced Data Protection =E2=80=94 which fully enc=
rypts iCloud backups =E2=80=94 even though it is off by default. In this li=
ght, the U.K. demanding that Advanced Data Encryption have a backdoor put i=
n it is in fact demanding a restoration to that uneasy compromise position.=
